@page "/help"
@rendermode @(new InteractiveWebAssemblyRenderMode(prerender: false))

@using BgQuiz_Blazor.Client.Quiz

@inject QuizController Controller
@inject NavigationManager Nav

<PageTitle>BgQuiz — Help</PageTitle>

<div class="container py-3" style="max-width:800px">
    <h1>How BgQuiz works</h1>

    <p class="lead">
        BgQuiz turns your own eXtreme Gammon analysis into practice: it shows you a
        position from one of your files, you answer it, and it scores your answer
        against XG's evaluation of that position.
    </p>

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">Pick your files</h2>
    <p>
        On the home page, choose one or more of your local <code>.xg</code> match files
        or <code>.xgp</code> position files. They are read and parsed entirely in your
        browser — nothing is uploaded, and no file ever leaves your machine. A single
        pick accepts up to @PickedFileLimits.MaxFileCount files, each up to
        @(PickedFileLimits.MaxFileMegabytes) MB.
    </p>

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">Choose filters</h2>
    <p>
        The filter panel narrows which decisions the quiz will ask you. You can restrict
        by decision type (checker plays, cube decisions, or both), by player, by how
        costly the recorded mistake was, and more. Filters must be <strong>applied</strong>
        before Start becomes available — editing any control un-applies them until you
        press Apply again. Optionally tick <em>Shuffle order</em> to see positions in a
        random order rather than in file order.
    </p>

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">Answer the position</h2>
    <p>
        Each problem is one of two kinds, and the board tells you which:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <strong>Checker play.</strong> The dice are rolled, and you enter the play you
            would make by clicking the board — see <em>Making a checker play</em> below.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Cube decision.</strong> The board is read-only. Answer with the radio
            buttons beside the Submit button: what the player on roll should do
            (double or not), and how the opponent should respond (take or pass).
        </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        Press <em>Submit</em> to answer, or <em>Skip</em> to move on without answering.
    </p>

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">Making a checker play</h2>
    <p>
        Plays are entered with single clicks — there is nothing to drag, and no
        pick-up-and-put-down. The board updates after every click, and only clicks that keep
        a legal full play reachable are accepted — anything else simply does nothing, so you
        cannot build an illegal play, and you cannot leave part of the roll unplayed when it
        could have been played. Landing on a lone opposing checker hits it automatically.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <strong>Clicking on a point you occupy moves a checker from there:</strong> it
            advances by one die straight away. When either die could play from that point, the
            <em>leftmost</em> die shown on the board is used — click the dice to swap them
            (see below). When the move carries the checker off the board, it bears off; that
            is just an ordinary move.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Clicking on a point that's empty or contains an opposing blot brings
            checkers there.</strong> If the point can be made, it is: two of your checkers land
            on it in the fewest moves, hitting anything in the way. With ordinary dice that
            uses both and finishes the play; with doubles you may still have dice left. If the
            point cannot be made, one checker that can reach it goes there instead. When there
            are two equally short ways to do it, the click does nothing; make the moves one at
            a time instead. This works even while you have a checker on the bar — see
            <em>Clicking on the bar</em>.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Clicking on the bar enters a checker</strong>, and always works while you
            have one there. When both dice could enter, the <em>leftmost</em> die is used —
            swap the dice to enter on the other point, or click the entry point directly. While
            any checker of yours is on the bar it must enter before anything else can move —
            but you can still click any point that is empty or holds an opposing blot: the
            entry happens first, and the rest of the roll brings a checker to the point you
            clicked. That checker need not be the one that entered — with a 2-1 from the bar,
            clicking an opposing blot in your home board enters with the two and hits with the
            one, as long as there is exactly one way to do it. Clicking a point you occupy does
            nothing while you are on the bar, even one the entering checker could reach: enter
            first, then move normally.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Clicking on the checker tray bears off as many checkers as the roll
            allows</strong>, whenever there is a unique way to do it. If two ways bear off
            equally many, the tray does nothing — bear off point by point instead, by clicking
            each checker's own point.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Click the dice to swap them, or to submit.</strong> While the play is
            unfinished, clicking the dice swaps the order they are shown in — which changes
            which one a checker click uses — without disturbing the moves you have already
            made. (Doubles have nothing to swap.) Once the play is finished, clicking the dice
            submits it, exactly as the <em>Submit</em> button does.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Change your mind — <em>Undo last</em> and <em>Undo all</em>.</strong> Undo
            last takes back the most recent move; Undo all restores the starting position.
            <em>Submit</em> stays disabled until the whole roll has been played.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">Scoring</h2>
    <p>
        A submitted answer is scored against XG's analysis of that position. Correct means
        you chose a play or action with no equity loss; otherwise the equity you gave up is
        recorded. Skipped problems are counted separately and never affect your accuracy.
        Scores are kept in four buckets: checker plays, doubling decisions, take decisions,
        and the total across all three.
    </p>

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">Review the solution</h2>
    <p>
        After you submit, the board switches to the solution view: XG's full analysis panel,
        with the recorded play marked <strong>*</strong> and your answer marked
        <strong>†</strong> when it differs. <em>Continue</em> moves to the next problem;
        <em>Redo</em> takes back your answer and returns you to the same position to try
        again.
    </p>

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">Stats and finishing</h2>
    <p>
        <em>Show stats</em> opens a running scoreboard at any point mid-quiz, and returns you
        to exactly where you were. When the last problem is answered you land on the summary
        page, where you can restart with the same filters or start over with new ones.
    </p>

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">Things worth knowing</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <strong>Positions with no legal play are skipped for you.</strong> When the dice
            leave the player on roll nothing to do, the position is passed over silently —
            you never see it, and it does not count as a skip.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>A play XG never listed counts as a skip, not a wrong answer.</strong> If
            you submit a legal play that isn't among the analyzed candidates, there is no
            equity loss to record against it, so it scores as a skip. You still see the
            solution.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>A cube position is two decisions, not one.</strong> The double and the
            take are scored independently, so one cube problem contributes one doubling
            decision and one take decision to your totals.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Clicking the dice advances.</strong> On the solution view, clicking the
            dice on the board does exactly what <em>Continue</em> does.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Reloading the browser starts you over.</strong> Moving between pages
            inside the app is always safe — your files, filters, and progress are kept. But a
            full browser reload (F5) discards all of it, and you will need to pick your files
            again.
        </li>
    </ul>

    @if (Controller.HasStarted && !Controller.IsFinished)
    {
        <button class="btn btn-primary mt-3" @onclick="BackToQuiz">
            Back to quiz
        </button>
    }
</div>
